# solid-docstring.cursorrules

name: "Python SOLID + Docstring Enforcement"
description: "Generate Python code following SOLID principles and include docstrings for all public classes, methods, and functions."

triggers:
  - "*.py"

rules:
  - id: enforce-single-responsibility
    description: "Each class should have one clear responsibility."
    instruction: |
      When generating classes, ensure they encapsulate a single responsibility.
      Split functionality into separate classes if multiple concerns are mixed.

  - id: enforce-open-closed
    description: "Classes should be open for extension but closed for modification."
    instruction: |
      Prefer abstract base classes or interfaces for extensibility.
      Avoid editing existing class internals when adding new features.

  - id: enforce-liskov-substitution
    description: "Subtypes must be substitutable for their base types."
    instruction: |
      Ensure derived classes honor the contracts of their base classes.
      Avoid breaking expected behavior when overriding methods.

  - id: enforce-interface-segregation
    description: "Clients should not depend on methods they do not use."
    instruction: |
      Generate small, focused interfaces.
      Avoid bloated classes with unused methods.

  - id: enforce-dependency-inversion
    description: "Depend on abstractions, not concretions."
    instruction: |
      Use dependency injection and abstract classes.
      Avoid hardcoding dependencies inside classes.

  - id: enforce-docstrings
    description: "All public classes, methods, and functions must include docstrings."
    instruction: |
      Generate docstrings in Google-style format:
      ```
      def foo(bar: int) -> str:
          """
          Brief summary of function.

          Args:
              bar (int): Description of parameter.

          Returns:
              str: Description of return value.
          """
      ```
      Ensure every function, class, and module has a descriptive docstring.
